# PIR Sensor + LED (Arduino) ‚Äî Quick README

## üìù Overview

A **PIR (Passive Infrared) sensor** detects motion by sensing changes in infrared radiation emitted by warm objects (like humans or animals). It is widely used in motion-activated lights, security systems, and automatic switches.

This project connects a PIR sensor to an Arduino. When movement is detected, an LED turns ON.

---

## üîß Components Required

* Arduino (UNO/Nano/Pro Mini)
* PIR Sensor (HC-SR501 or similar)
* LED + 220Œ© resistor
* Jumper wires

---

## üîå Connections

| Component         | Arduino Pin |
| ----------------- | ----------- |
| PIR OUT           | **Pin 2**   |
| LED (+)           | **Pin 8**   |
| GND (PIR & LED)** | **GND**     |
| VCC (PIR)         | **5V**      |

---

## ‚û°Ô∏è How the PIR Sensor Works

* PIR detects **motion** based on infrared radiation changes.
* When motion is detected ‚Üí output becomes **HIGH**.
* When no motion ‚Üí output stays **LOW**.

---

## üí° Arduino Code

```cpp
int pirPin = 2;      // PIR sensor connected to pin 2
int ledPin = 8;      // LED connected to pin 8
int pirState = LOW;  // To store PIR sensor status

void setup() {
  pinMode(pirPin, INPUT);  
  pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);

  Serial.begin(9600);   // Optional: to see output on Serial Monitor
}

void loop() {
  int value = digitalRead(pirPin); // Read PIR sensor

  if (value == HIGH) {
    digitalWrite(ledPin, HIGH);  // Turn ON the LED
    Serial.println("Motion Detected");
  } else {
    digitalWrite(ledPin, LOW);   // Turn OFF the LED
    Serial.println("No Motion");
  }

  delay(200); // Small delay for stability
}
```

---

## ‚úîÔ∏è Summary

* PIR sensor detects motion ‚Üí Arduino receives HIGH signal.
* Arduino turns on LED at pin 8.
* Simple and ideal for motion-activated systems.

If you want a version with a **timer**, **buzzer**, or **delay-based auto off**, just ask!

